/gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/C3C96CB6-B810-4A88-9E65-6A5B20342976"><gtr:id>C3C96CB6-B810-4A88-9E65-6A5B20342976</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Jonathan</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Mark</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Shaw</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/6867C190-3E6C-4E53-BD33-C01F14A8B74F"><gtr:id>6867C190-3E6C-4E53-BD33-C01F14A8B74F</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Monica</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Costa</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Dias</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=ES%2FI028021%2F1"><gtr:id>1931BF25-BD4F-4A46-8E8E-F797B384E2E5</gtr:id><gtr:title>A lifetime perspective on the distributional and incentive effects of the tax system</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I028021/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Modern tax (and benefits) systems affect the intertemporal incentives to work and invest in human capital over the lifecourse by, eg, changing the income-age profile, insuring against adversities or altering the returns to human capital through redistribution. But most existing work on the effects of the tax system ignores any dynamic considerations.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This project aims to provide a richer understanding of the UK tax system and its effects on individuals' decisions to invest in human capital and work, lifetime income and wellbeing. The following questions are addressed: &lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>How do financial incentives to work change over the lifecourse?&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>How is the tax burden shared over the population and over the lifecourse?&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>What are the effects of changes in taxes/benefits on the distribution of lifetime income, incentives to work and invest in human capital? &lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>The research is based on the analysis of simulated lifetimes of individuals whose characteristics are taken from survey data, and whose decisions are based on a lifecycle model of human capital accumulation, work and family formation representing the real lifecourse. The model includes a detailed description of the UK tax system to fully capture its effect on the incentives to work and invest in human capital.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-10-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>87310</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>In-work benefits and dynamic female education and labour supply</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>B0E75B70-6B25-474F-AF55-030C40422CBA</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Presentation given to the Advisory Commitee for the ESRC 'Centre for the Microeconomic Analysis of Public Policy'.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Supporters</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.ifs.org.uk/centres/esrcIndex</gtr:url><gtr:year>2011</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Income Dynamics, Income Risk, and Income Risk-Sharing</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>E856F5C2-CACF-42F9-B94F-35A6A89C9208</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This workshop was held at the University of Atlanta in September 2013.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Other